<subSubSection id="C3466570486D975AFF2DF9D99BC417F1" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE336FB486D975AFF2DF9D99BC417F1" blockId="17.[192,1440,1635,1691]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="B928EAE9486D975AFF2DF9D99B7D1711" bold="true" box="[192,349,1635,1659]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C5C4D78486D975AFD81F9D998E01711" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2010" box="[620,704,1635,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Madoniella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spilota">
<emphasis id="B928EAE9486D975AFD81F9D998E01711" box="[620,704,1635,1659]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">spilota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stems from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B928EAE9486D975AFC0EF9D99E0A1711" box="[995,1066,1635,1659]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">spilos</emphasis>
(= fleck). I refer to the spotty infuscations on the legs.
</paragraph>
